03809nam a22005175i 9780773576124DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735761247 a10.1515/97807735761242doi  a(DE-B1597)657336  a(OCoLC)741350267  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1034.3.D5.M36 2009eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971.06421 aMcMahon, Patricia I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEssence of Indecision :bDiefenbaker's Nuclear Policy, 1957-1963 /cPatricia I. McMahon. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tThe Conservatives Return to Power, 1957–1958 -- tDiefenbaker and Defence Policy, 1958–1959 -- tCanada’s Nuclear Policy Takes Shape, 1959–1960 -- tA Period of Transition, 1960–1961 -- tNuclear Negotiations and the 1962 Federal Election -- tTo the Brink and Beyond: The Cuban Missile Crisis and Canada’s Nuclear Policy -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTracing Diefenbaker's deliberations over nuclear policy, McMahon shows that Diefenbaker was politically cautious, not indecisive - he wanted to acquire nuclear weapons and understood from public opinion polls that most Canadians supported this position. However, Diefenbaker worried that the growing anti-nuclear movement might sway public opinion sufficiently to undermine his political support. He also feared that Liberal leader Lester Pearson could use the issue for political advantage. As long as Pearson opposed Canada's membership in the nuclear club, he could portray Diefenbaker's government as an irresponsible proponent of nuclear proliferation. Despite these reservations, Diefenbaker was involved in nuclear negotiations with the Americans throughout his tenure as prime minister, and an agreement was within reach on a number of occasions. When, in January 1963, Pearson reversed his position, Diefenbaker felt trapped - in making a clear public statement in favour of nuclear weapons it would appear as though he was merely following his opponent's lead. When Canada acquired nuclear weapons in 1963, it was under the leadership of Pearson, not Diefenbaker.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNuclear weaponsxGovernment policyzCanadaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357612440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773576124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773576124/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles